'''Herbert Ihlefeld''' (1 June 1914 <U+2013> 8 August 1995) was a [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[World War II]] [[flying ace|fighter ace]] who served in the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' from 1936 until the very end of [[World War II]] in May 1945. He was also a recipient of the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] with Oak Leaves and Swords. The Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross and its higher grade Oak Leaves and Swords was awarded to recognise extreme battlefield bravery or successful military leadership. He claimed 132 enemy aircraft shot down; nine in the [[Spanish Civil War]], 67 on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], and 56 on the [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]], including 15 four-engined bombers and 26 [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]]s. He survived being shot down eight times during his 1,000 combat missions.

==World War II==
Ihlefeld was born on 1 June 1914 in [[Hohenselchow-Gro<U+00DF> Pinnow|Pinnow]], (at the time in the [[Province of Pomerania (1815<U+2013>1945)|Province of Pomerania]]), a [[Provinces of Prussia|province]] of the [[Kingdom of Prussia]]. In August 1938, he was assigned to the I(J)./[[Lehrgeschwader 2|''Lehrgeschwader'' 2]] (LG 2<U+2014>2nd Demonstration Wing), an operational training unit. He flew in the [[invasion of Poland]], and in the [[battle of France|battles of]] France and [[Battle of Britain|Britain]]. In July 1940, "Ihle" was now ''[[Staffelkapit<U+00E4>n]]'' (squadron leader) of 1.(J)/LG 2, leading it during the Battle of Britain. He was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross|''Ritterkreuz'']] during September 1940, for 24 claimed kills.

In April 1941, the unit was transferred to the Balkans to take part in the [[invasion of Yugoslavia]]. During one of his first missions, strafing an airfield near [[Ni<U+0161>]], Ihlefeld was shot down by anti-aircraft fire and captured by Yugoslavian soldiers. While in their custody, he was allegedly severely beaten, and threatened with execution by firing squad. He was rescued by German troops after eight days in captivity, and returned to Germany to recover. After a few weeks, "Ihle" returned to participate in the [[Battle of Crete|assault on Crete]], claiming a [[Hawker Hurricane]] shot down for his 36th claim. Soon after, ''LG 2'' was rearmed and remustered as I./[[Jagdgeschwader 77|''Jagdgeschwader'' 77]] (JG 77<U+2014>77th Fighter Wing) in time for [[Operation Barbarossa|Operation ''Barbarossa'']], the German invasion of the Soviet Union in June 1941, Ihlefeld retaining  command of ''I./JG 77''.

In the spring of 1942, a series of multiple victories (five aircraft on 24 March, seven on 30 March and seven on 20 April), saw Ihlefeld become the fifth pilot to reach 100 victories. During the period of Ihlefeld's leadership, ''I./JG 77'' was credited with the destruction of 323 enemy aircraft while losing only 17 [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]s.

In June 1942, Ihlefeld became ''[[Geschwaderkommodore]]'' (Wing Commander) of the famed [[Jagdgeschwader 52|''Jagdgeschwader'' 52]] (JG 52<U+2014>52nd Fighter Wing). On 22 July 1942, whilst flying over the front in his [[Fieseler Fi 156 Storch|''Storch'']], he was shot down and badly wounded by Soviet fighters,<ref>J. S. A. Hayward 1998, p.146</ref> this took him out of the front line until July 1943, when he joined the newly formed ''Jagdgeschwader'' 25 as ''Geschwaderkommodore'', leading the group's high-altitude Bf 109s in ultimately unsuccessful operations against [[Royal Air Force]] [[de Havilland Mosquito|Mosquito]]s, and later [[United States Air Force]] (USAAF) heavy bomber formations in [[Defense of the Reich|''Reichsverteidigung'']] missions.

In May 1944, he became ''Geschwaderkommodore'' of ''[[Jagdgeschwader 11]]'' (JG 11<U+2014>11th Fighter Wing), briefly before switching to ''Geschwaderkommodore'' of [[Jagdgeschwader 1 (World War 2)|''Jagdgeschwader'' 1]] (JG 1<U+2014>1st Fighter Wing), overseeing the period where elements of the ''Geschwader'' were equipped late in the war with the [[Heinkel He 162|He 162 ''Volksj<U+00E4>ger'']].

==Awards==
* Spanish ''[[Medalla Militar]]''<ref name="Berger p139">Berger 2000, p. 139.</ref>
* [[Spanish Cross]] in Silver with Swords<ref name="Berger p139"/>
* [[Wound Badge]] in Black<ref name="Berger p139"/>
* [[Front Flying Clasp of the Luftwaffe|Front Flying Clasp of the ''Luftwaffe'']] in Gold with Pennant "1000"<ref name="Berger p139"/>
* [[Combined Pilots-Observation Badge]]<ref name="Berger p139"/>
* [[Iron Cross]] (1939) 
** 2nd Class (26 September 1939)<ref name="Thomas p317">Thomas 1997, p. 317.</ref>
** 1st Class (4 July 1940)<ref name="Thomas p317"/>
* ''[[Ehrenpokal der Luftwaffe]]'' (12 June 1941)<ref>Obermaier 1989, p. 31.</ref>
* [[German Cross]] in Gold on 9 April 1942 as ''[[Hauptmann]]'' in the I./JG 77<ref>Patzwall and Scherzer 2001, p. 204.</ref>
* [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross|Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves and Swords]]
** Knight's Cross on 13 September 1940 as ''[[Oberleutnant]]'' and pilot in the I./JG 77<ref>Fellgiebel 2000, p. 239.</ref>{{#tag:ref|According to Scherzer in the I.(J)/LG 2<ref name="Scherzer p413">Scherzer 2007, p. 413.</ref>|group="Notes"}}
** 16th Oak Leaves on 27 June 1941 as ''Hauptmann'' and ''[[Gruppenkommandeur]]'' of the I./JG 77<ref name="Scherzer p413"/><ref>Fellgiebel 2000, p. 54.</ref>
** 9th Swords on 24 April 1942 as ''Hauptmann'' and ''Gruppenkommandeur'' of the ''I./JG 77''<ref name="Scherzer p413"/><ref>Fellgiebel 2000, p. 39.</ref>
* Mentioned six times in the ''[[Wehrmachtbericht]]''

